Introduction to Open Data Science - Course Project

About the project

The course “Introduction to Open Data Science” makes for an interesting, engaging start to some of the softwares and programming that appear daunting at first. Starting right away with practice sets on R and GitHub, the course effectively deals with the initial hesitation of getting started on both of these platforms, with the help of the book “R for Health Data Science”. The introduction to various data types and operations may be a slow start, but the next chapters quickly start becoming interesting. As the course progresses towards methods for data analysis and visualization, and its application to one’s own research becomes obvious, it becomes even more engaging and builds more motivation to learn more ways to use these freely available resources for one’s own research. Please find the link to my GitHub repository below:

GitHub Repository

https://github.com/MeghaKWII/IODS-project

Creating an Analysis dataset

As previosly mentioned,this dataset records variables to assess learning, understanding and attitudes of people towards statistics. The next steps take a look at some of these variables, namely

  • Attitude: Global attitude toward statistics

  • Deep: Deep approach to learning, which involves gaining an in-depth understanding

  • Surf: Surface approach, consisting primarily of memorizing without understanding

  • Stra: Strategic approach, which students apply in the face of constraints such as deadlines and syllabus

1. Scaling vectors to their original values:

Now, to create an analysis dataset, we need to keep in mind that some parameters are aggregates of two or more variables. These are:

  1. Attitude = Da + Db + Dc + Dd + De + Df + Dg + Dh + Di + Dj

  2. Deep = d_sm + d_ri + d_ue, and

  • d_sm = D03 + D11 + D19 + D27

  • d_ri = D07 + D14 + D22 + D30

  • d_ue = D06 + D15 + D23 + D31

  1. Stra = st_os + st_tm, where

  • st_os = ST01 + ST09 + ST17 + ST25

  • st_tm = ST04 + ST12 + ST20 + ST28

  1. Surf = su_lp + su_um + su_sb, where

  • su_lp = SU02 + SU10 + SU18 + SU26

  • su_um = SU05 + SU13 + SU21 + SU29

  • su_sb = SU08 + SU16 + SU24 + SU32

In order to scale Attitude, we need to divide it by the number of variables that constitute it.This is easily done by creating a new variable and assigning the new value to it

Hence,

# divide each number in the column "Attitude" by 10

# create column 'attitude' by scaling the column "Attitude"
learn$attitude <- learn$Attitude / 10

Now for the other variables, since “deep”, “Surf” and “stra” do not exist in this dataset, we must create them by aggregating and averaging their constituents

But first, lemme access the dplyr library

library(dplyr)

# questions related to deep, surface and strategic learning
deep_questions <- c("D03", "D11", "D19", "D27", "D07", "D14", "D22", "D30","D06",  "D15", "D23", "D31")
surface_questions <- c("SU02","SU10","SU18","SU26", "SU05","SU13","SU21","SU29","SU08","SU16","SU24","SU32")
strategic_questions <- c("ST01","ST09","ST17","ST25","ST04","ST12","ST20","ST28")

# select the columns related to deep learning 
deep_columns <- select(learn, one_of(deep_questions))
# and create column 'deep' by averaging
learn$deep <- rowMeans(deep_columns)

# select the columns related to surface learning 
surface_columns <- select(learn, one_of(surface_questions))
# and create column 'surf' by averaging
learn$surf <- rowMeans(surface_columns)

# select the columns related to strategic learning 
strategic_columns <- select(learn, one_of(strategic_questions))
# and create column 'stra' by averaging
learn$stra <- rowMeans(strategic_columns)
# and create column 'stra' by averaging

Explaining the model

Model “d” uses the variables “stra”, “Age” and “Attitude” to explain the variations in the target variable , “Points”.

Relationships between variables

  • Both strategic learning and age have a statistically significant, direct relationship with the points obtained by a student in the examination. These explanatory variables are significant at the 0.1 level, meaning this significance also accounts for 1 % of error in the model.

  • The attitude of the students has a significant, direct relationship with the points obtained by a student in the examination. This relationship is significant at the 0.000 level, accounting for 0 % error.

R-squared

The multiple R-squared value of 0.2182 denotes that the model can accurately explain 21.82% of variations in points, using the three explanatory variables.

Validating the Model

The model’s validity will be tested using diagnostic plots using the plot() function.

# Producing diagnostic plots for the model "d"
plot(d)

Residuals v/s Fitted

  • The residuals are distributed randomly and do not have any obvious patterns (although it also appears that more residuals fall above zero). On the whole, the plot indicates that the values deviate more or less randomly from the values predicted by the model.

    • This suggests that the relationship between the variables is more or less linear.

  • There appear to be a few outliers (points 56, 145 and 35).

Normal QQ-plot
  • Not all points coincide with the line, and there appear to be some negative residuals (those falling below the line). This suggests that the data may be skewed and not perfectly normally distributed.
Residuals v/s Leverage
  • The lines indicating Cook’s distance are not visible in our Residuals v/s Leverage Plot. This indicates that all points fall within Cook’s distance. If any points had lied beyond Cook’s distance, they would be the most influential points in our data, removing which could potentially change the interpretation of the model. Therefore, we can assume that model “d” does not have any such points.

About the data and hypotheses

The data studies student performance in secondary education of two Portuguese schools. The data attributes include student grades, demographic, social and school related features, in the context of their performance in two distinct subjects, Mathematics and Portuguese language. In this chapter, we are interested in observing the relationship of alcohol consumption by students with some selected parameters. For this, we formulate the following hypotheses:

  • Alcohol consumption varies significantly with age (age), with older students consuming more alcohol than younger students

  • Alcohol consumption varies significantly with engagement in extra-curricular activities (activities), with students engaging in extracurricular activities consuming lesser alcohol.

  • Alcohol consumption varies significantly with the quality of family relationship (Famrel), with a better quality associated with lower alcohol consumption.

  • Alcohol consumption varies significantly with the student’s frequency of going out with friends (goout), higher frequency associated with higher alcohol consumption.

Numerically and graphically testing hypotheses

We will use cross-tables to numerically explore the data to see if any of our hypotheses are correct.

Model:

Generalized Linear Models allow us to perform linear regressions for data that are not normally distributed. Since there are categorical variables, we cannot run linear regressions with normal distributions. We will therefore use the glm function with a binomial distribution.

# Converting factors back to numeric for modeling
alc$age <- as.numeric(alc$age)
alc$famrel <- as.numeric(alc$famrel)
alc$goout <- as.numeric(alc$goout)
m <- glm(high_use ~ age + activities + famrel + goout, data = alc, family = "binomial")
summary(m)

Model Interpretation:

Of the four variables, only two have a significant (p<0.01) influence on whether or not the alcohol consumption by a student is high:

  1. The quality of their relationship with their family, and

  2. Their frequency of going out.

However, the Odds Ratios tell a different story:

  1. The Odds Ratio reveals a strong association (>1) between age and alcohol consumption, meaning the likelihood of high alcohol consumption rises with age.

  2. The strongest association still exists between alcohol consumption and the frequency of going out.

Predictive Power:

# Adding a column that displays the output for whether alcohol consumption is high or not, based on the model
## We first add a column that computes the probability for high alcohol consumption using our model

alc <- mutate(alc, probability = predict(m, type = "response"))

## If the probability is greater than 50% (or 0.5), the model will predict high alcohol consumption to be "True", and otherwise, "False". These outputs will be displayed in another column.  We call this column "prediction"

alc <- mutate(alc, prediction = probability > 0.5)




# Tabulating the target variable versus the predictions
table(high_use = alc$high_use, prediction = alc$prediction)
##         prediction
## high_use FALSE TRUE
##    FALSE   235   24
##    TRUE     71   40
# Plotting the predictive power
g <- ggplot(alc, aes(x = "probability", y = "high use")) + geom_point()

g

From the table, it appears that the present model can fairly reliably predict when alcohol consumption is not high, but it can predict conditions of high alcohol consumption to be false as well. We will attempt to estimate the average number of wrongly classified students in the next steps:

# define a loss function (mean prediction error)
loss_func <- function(class, prob) {
  n_wrong <- abs(class - prob) > 0.5
  mean(n_wrong)
}

loss_func(class = alc$high_use, prob = 0)
## [1] 0.3

Therefore, the mean prediction error of this model is 0.3, meaning there is a 30% possibility of an instance being wrongly classified as “False” for high alcohol consumption.

Relationships between variables:

We will start with the per capita crime rate (crime) as it is the parameter we will be observing in this exercise

  1. The crime rate shows a highy positive correlation with

  • higher proportion of non-retail businesses (indus),

  • nitrous oxide levels (nox),

  • accessibility to radial highways (rad), and

  • property tax rates (tax)

  1. Crime rate is negatively correlated with:

  • Distance to the employment centres (dis)

  • Proportion of the black population (black) (Racists will say this is fake)

  • value of owner-occupied homes (medv)

  1. The most strongly correlated variables:

  • proportion of non-retail businesses and distance to the employment centres: negative correlation

  • proportion of non-retail businesses and nitrous oxide levels: positive correlation (makes sense- industrialization and not very healthy emissions go hand in hand)

  • proportion of owner-occupied units built prior to 1940 (age) and distance to the employment centres: negative correlation (It appears the employment centres were built away from residential areas)

Converting the new scaled crime rate (crim) to factor with the quantiles as intervals. We will label this variable “crime”:

boston_scaled$crim <- as.numeric(boston_scaled$crim)

bins <- quantile(boston_scaled$crim)


boston_scaled$crime <- cut(boston_scaled$crim, breaks = bins, include.lowest = TRUE, labels = c("low", "med_low", "med_high", "high"))

boston_scaled <- dplyr::select(boston_scaled, -crim)

The new variable “crime” has been divided into four levels:

  • -0.419 to -0.411 (low)

  • -0.411 to -0.39 (med_low)

  • -0.39 to 0.00739 (med_high)

  • 0.00739 to 9.92 (high)

set.seed(123)
k_max <- 10

# calculate the total within sum of squares
twcss <- sapply(1:k_max, function(k){kmeans(Boston, k)$tot.withinss})

qplot(x = 1:k_max, y = twcss, geom = 'line')

# plot the Boston dataset with clusters
pairs(Boston, col = km$cluster)

It does appear that the within-cluster variability changes considerably when we change the number of clusters from 1 to 2 and 3. However, the lowest value is obtained at around 8-9.

There are some obvious differences between the results of a PCA between the original and standardized data:

  • PC1 explains 100% of the variations within the original dataset, but for the scaled dataset, PC1 explains nearly 58% of variations and PC2 explains nearly 15% of the variations.

  • Maternal Mortality Ratio (MMR) and Per Capita Gross National Income (GNI) appear to be the most influential variabled in the unscaled dataset.

  • In the scaled dataset, Life Expectancy, Expected years of Education, Per Capita Gross National Income, Proportion of Women with Higher Education, Proportion of women representation in the Parliament, Proportion of Women in the labour force, Maternal Mortality Ratio and Adolescent Births all make comparable comtribution to the variations.

  • Taking into account the direction of the variables, the two datasets give us the following information:

    • Unscaled dataset: PC1 reflects the Gross National Income and PC2 reflects Maternal Mortality Ratio and Adolescent Births.

    • Scaled dataset: PC1 reflects indices of well-being, such as life expectancy, expected years of formal education, maternal mortality ratio, etc., while PC2 reflects the effect of these indices of well-being on servoces to the society, such as representation by women in the parliament and the labour force.

  • The above observation in interesting especially in comparison to the correlation matrix, where neither women representation in the parliament or the labour force had very strong correlations with other factors. The PCA of the scaled dataset does show these variables to be directed in a different direction than most other variables.

Data:

The RATS dataset:

DT::datatable(RATS, options = list(pageLength = 10))

The above data studies the temporal trends in the weight of rats, taking repeated measurements from each week, group and individual. These variables could potentially contribute to correlations between individual weights.

Graphical Representation

RATS$timef <- factor(RATS$Time)
RATS$group <- factor(RATS$Group)
p <- ggplot(data = RATS, aes(x = timef, y = Weight)) + geom_boxplot() + geom_jitter(aes(col = group)) + xlab("Time (days") + ylab("Weight (g)")
p

The above plot indicates weight ranging from approximately 200 g to 500 g for the rats on day 1, which increased to approximately 300 g - 650 g by day 64. Group 1 had the lowest weights throughout the study.

Taking a closer look at each treatment:

p2 <- ggplot(data = RATS, aes(x = timef, y = Weight)) + geom_point(aes(col = group)) + xlab("Time (days)") + ylab("Weight (g)")
  
 p2 <- p2 + facet_wrap(~group)
 p2

There are quite some variations in Group 2. Wonder if these are contributed by the same individual. Let’s take a yet closer look at this group.

RATS$individual <- factor(RATS$ID)

p3 <- ggplot(data = RATS, aes(x = timef, y = Weight)) + geom_point(aes(col = individual)) + xlab("Time (days)") + ylab("Weight (g)")

p3 <- p3 + facet_wrap(~group)
 p3

As suspected, the variation is contributed to by one individual, ID 12.

From the above graphs, it appears that time and group may have a significant influence on the weight of the individuals. The individuals themselves may present some variations, and these may need to be accounted for (especially ID 12).

We’ll try to see if our hypothesis is correct, using ANOVA.

#let's create a summary dataset first
RATS.s <- RATS %>%            
  filter(ID != 12) %>%                   #We'll remove ID 12, which is causing a lot of variation within Group 2
  group_by(Group, ID) %>%
  summarise( mean=mean(Weight) ) %>%
  ungroup()
